2274	% SOURCE QUOTE PROOF: (Archon-original assembly from the Stacks stalk-tensor lemma
2275	% above and the stalkwise criterion for membership in the sheafification localizer;
2276	% no single external source proof.)
2277	\begin{proof}
2278	  \leanok
2279	  \uses{lem:stalk_tensor_commutation, lem:stalk_linear_map,
2280	    lem:W_implies_stalkwise_iso, lem:stalk_tensor_commutation_naturality_right}
2281	  The proof runs in three movements: the d.1-bridge turns membership in \(J.W\) into a
2282	  stalkwise statement, the second-factor naturality of the d.2 isomorphism transports
2283	  the whiskered stalk into a tensor of the stalk maps, and a flatness-free
2284	  ``tensoring by an equivalence'' argument concludes.
2285	
2286	  \emph{(a) The d.1-bridge.} Specialise to the topological site \(\mathtt{Opens}\,X\),
2287	  where stalks exist. By the hypothesis \(g \in J.W\) and the d.1-bridge
2288	  \cref{lem:W_implies_stalkwise_iso}, the \(\mathtt{Ab}\)-stalk map \(g_x : M_x \to N_x\)
2289	  is an isomorphism at every point \(x \in X\). By \cref{lem:stalk_linear_map} this
2290	  stalk map carries an \(R_x\)-linear structure, and the bijectivity just obtained
2291	  upgrades it to an \(R_x\)-linear equivalence
2292	  \(\mathtt{stalkLinearEquivOfIsIso} : M_x \xrightarrow{\sim} N_x\).
2293	
2294	  \emph{(b) Identifying the whiskered stalk.} By the second-factor naturality of the
2295	  stalk--tensor comparison \cref{lem:stalk_tensor_commutation_naturality_right}, the
2296	  isomorphism \(\mathtt{stalkTensorIso}\) of \cref{lem:stalk_tensor_commutation}
2297	  identifies the stalk \((F \triangleleft g)_x\) of the whiskered morphism with the
2298	  map
2299	  \[
2300	    \mathrm{id}_{F_x} \otimes g_x \;=\; \mathtt{LinearMap.lTensor}\,F_x\,g_x
2301	      \;\colon\; F_x \otimes_{R_x} M_x \longrightarrow F_x \otimes_{R_x} N_x .
2302	  \]
2303	
2304	  \emph{(c) Conclusion.} Tensoring the \(R_x\)-linear equivalence
2305	  \(g_x : M_x \xrightarrow{\sim} N_x\) of (a) on the left by the identity of \(F_x\)
2306	  yields an \(R_x\)-linear equivalence
2307	  \(\mathtt{LinearMap.lTensor}\,F_x\,g_x = \mathrm{id}_{F_x} \otimes g_x\)
2308	  (this is \(\mathtt{LinearEquiv.lTensor}\); it needs \emph{no} flatness of \(F_x\),
2309	  because lifting an isomorphism through \(F_x \otimes_{R_x} (-)\) only uses the
2310	  functoriality of the tensor product, and the inverse is supplied by the inverse
2311	  equivalence). By (b), \((F \triangleleft g)_x\) is therefore an isomorphism of
2312	  \(\mathtt{Ab}\)-stalks for every \(x\). Applying the converse half of the d.1-bridge
2313	  \cref{lem:W_implies_stalkwise_iso} to the morphism \(F \triangleleft g\) gives
2314	  \(F \triangleleft g \in J.W\), and in particular it is \(J\)-locally injective
2315	  (\(\mathtt{GrothendieckTopology.W.isLocallyInjective}\)). No flatness, no local
2316	  triviality, and the whiskering object \(F\) is arbitrary.
2317	
2318	  The statement holds over any Grothendieck site \(J\) satisfying
2319	  \(J.\mathtt{WEqualsLocallyBijective}\,\mathtt{Ab}\), and is applied in particular
2320	  at the topological site \(\mathtt{Opens}\,X\) of a scheme, where the stalk
2321	  arguments of (a)--(c) are available and through which the unconditional associator
2322	  \cref{lem:tensorobj_assoc_iso} is realized.
2323	\end{proof}
